ts/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Independent/meta/color}};\" |\n|Independents\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\u2013\n|{{Composition bar|0|129|{{Independent/meta/color}}}}\n|{{Composition bar|2|129|{{Independent/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Presiding Officer of the Scottish Parliament/meta/color}};\" |\n|Presiding Officer\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\u2013\n|{{Composition bar|0|129|{{Presiding Officer of the Scottish Parliament/meta/color}}}}\n|{{Composition bar|1|129|{{Presiding Officer of the Scottish Parliament/meta/color}}}}\n|}\n\n==Election system, seats, and regions==\n{{main|Scottish Parliament constituencies and regions from 2011}}\nThe total number of [[Members of the Scottish Parliament]] (MSPs) elected to the Parliament is 129.\n\nThe Scottish Parliament uses an [[Additional Members System]], designed to produce approximate [[proportional representation]] for each region. There are 8 regions, each sub-divided into smaller constituencies. There are a total of 73 [[Scottish Parliament constituencies and regions|constituencies]]. Each constituency elects one MSP by the [[Plurality voting system|plurality]] ([[first past the post]]) system of election. Each region elects 7 additional MSPs using an [[Mixed member proportional representation|additional member]] system. \nA modified [[D'Hondt method]], using the constituency results, is used to elect these additional MSPs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/2840087.stm |title=Electoral system: How it works, 02 April 2003 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=2 April 2003 |accessdate=6 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/guides/newsid_8227000/8227617.stm |title=D'Hondt system |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=28 September 2009 |accessdate=4 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe boundaries of the 73 constituencies last changed as of the [[2011 Scottish Parliament election]], as did the configuration of the electoral regions used to elect \"list\" members of the Scottish Parliament,.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bcomm-scotland.gov.uk/1st_holyrood/rev_rec_regions/regions_revised_recommendations_map_A2.pdf |title=Revised Recommendations |publisher=Boundary Commission for Scotland |accessdate=26 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612043941/http://www.bcomm-scotland.gov.uk/1st_holyrood/rev_rec_regions/regions_revised_recommendations_map_A2.pdf |archive-date=12 June 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> These revisions were the outcome of the First Periodical Review of the [[Scottish Parliament constituencies and regions|Scottish Parliament's constituencies and regions]] conducted by the [[Boundary Commission for Scotland]]; the Review was announced on 3 July 2007 and the Commission published its final report on 26 May 2010.\n\nThe Scottish Parliament constituencies have not been coterminous with [[Scottish Westminster constituencies]] since the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], when the 72 former UK Parliament constituencies were replaced with a new set of 59, generally larger, constituencies (see [[Scottish Parliament (Constituencies) Act 2004]]). The size difference between Westminster and Holyrood boundaries was due to diverge further upon the implementation of the [[Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies]], which has not been voted upon by Parliament. Plans for the [[2021 Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies]] for a UK total of 650 MPs have been revealed by the UK Government.\n<!--\n==Campaign==\n*[[BBC Scotland]]\n*[[STV (TV channel)|STV]]\n\n==Policy platforms==\n\n==Parties contesting the election==\n\n===Contesting constituency and regional ballot===\n===Contesting regional ballot only===\n===Contesting constituency ballot only===\n\n==Election results==\n{{Scottish Parliament general election, 2016}}\n\n===Constituency and regional summary===\n====Central Scotland====\n\