onal Party]]: \n* [[UK Independence Party]]:\n* [[Women's Equality Party]]: \n-->\n{{Scottish elections}}\n\n[[Category:General elections to the Scottish Parliament]]\n[[Category:Future elections in the United Kingdom|Scotland]]\n[[Category:2021 elections in the United Kingdom|Scottish Parliament election]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Scottish English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = Next Scottish Parliament election\n| country = Scotland\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = yes\n| previous_election = 2016 Scottish Parliament election\n| previous_year = 2016\n| outgoing_members = 5th Scottish Parliament\n| elected_members = <!--6th Scottish Parliament-->\n| next_election = <!--2025 Scottish Parliament election-->\n| next_year = <!--2025-->\n| seats_for_election = All 129 seats to the [[Scottish Parliament]]\n| majority_seats = 65\n| opinion_polls = Opinion Polling for the Next Scottish Parliament Election\n| election_date = On or before 6 May 2021\n| 1blank = Regional vote\n| 2blank = % and swing\n| 3blank = Constituency&nbsp;vote\n| 4blank = % and swing\n| image1 = {{CSS image crop\n|Image         = Nicola Sturgeon election infobox 3.jpg\n|bSize         = 120\n|cWidth        = 120\n|cHeight       = 160\n|oLeft =\n|Location = center\n}}\n| leader1 = [[Nicola Sturgeon]]\n| leader_since1 = [[2014 Scottish National Party leadership election|14 November 2014]]\n| party1 = Scottish National Party\n| leaders_seat1 = [[Glasgow Southside (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Southside]]\n| last_election1 = 63 seats\n| seats_before1 = 61\n| seats_needed1 = {{increase}}4\n| seats1 = \n| seat_change1 = \n| 1data1 = \n| 2data1 = \n| 3data1 = \n| 4data1 = \n| image2 = {{CSS image crop\n|Image         = JacksonCarlawMSP20110509.JPG\n|bSize         = 136\n|cWidth        = 120\n|cHeight       = 160\n|oLeft =\n|Location = center\n}}\n| leader2 = [[Jackson Carlaw]]\n| party2 = Scottish Conservative Party\n| leaders_seat2 = [[Eastwood (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Eastwood]]\n| leader_since2 = [[2020 Scottish Conservative Party leadership election|14 February 2020]]\n| last_election2 = 31 seats\n| seats_before2 = 31\n| seats_needed2 = {{increase}}34\n| seats2 = \n| seat_change2 = \n| 1data2 = \n| 2data2 = \n| 3data2 = \n| 4data2 = \n| image3 = {{CSS image crop\n|Image        = RichardLeonardMSP.jpg\n|bSize         = 136\n|cWidth        = 120\n|cHeight       = 160\n|oLeft = 5\n|Location = center\n}}\n| leader3 = [[Richard Leonard (Scottish politician)|Richard Leonard]]\n| party3 = Scottish Labour Party\n| leaders_seat3 = [[Central Scotland (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Central Scotland]]\n| leader_since3 = [[2017 Scottish Labour leadership election|18 November 2017]]\n| last_election3 = 24 seats\n| seats_before3 = 23\n| seats_needed3 = {{increase}}42\n| seats3 = \n| seat_change3 = \n| 1data3 = \n| 2data3 = \n| 3data3 = \n| 4data3 = \n| image4 = {{CSS image crop\n|Image         = PatrickHarvieMSP20110510.JPG\n|bSize         = 150\n|cWidth        = 120\n|cHeight       = 160\n|oTop = 12\n|Location = center\n}}\n| leader4 = {{nowrap|[[Patrick Harvie]]}}<br />and [[Lorna Slater]]\n| party4 = Scottish Green Party\n| leader_since4 = Nov 2008&nbsp;/&nbsp;Aug 2019\n| leaders_seat4 = {{nowrap|[[Glasgow (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Glasgow]]}} /<br /><small>''Not an MSP''</small>\n| last_election4 = 6 seats\n| seats_before4 = 6\n| seats_needed4 = {{increase}}59\n| seats4 = \n| seat_change4 = \n| 1data4 = \n| 2data4 = \n| 3data4 = \n| 4data4 = \n| image5 = {{CSS image crop\n|Image         = Willie Rennie 2011 (cropped).JPG\n|bSize         = 120\n|cWidth        = 120\n|cHeight       = 160\n|oLeft =\n|Location = center\n}}\n| leader5 = [[Willie Rennie]]\n| party5 = Scottish Liberal Democrats\n| leaders_seat5 = [[North East Fife (Scottish Parliament constituency)|North East Fife]]\n| leader_since5 = {{nowrap|[[2011 Scottish Liberal Democrats leadership election|17 May 2011]]}}\n| last_election5 = 5 seats\n| seats_before5 = 5\n| seats_needed5 = {{increase}}60\n| seats5 = \n| seat_change5 = \n| 1data5 = \n| 2data5 = \n| 3data5 = \n| 4data5 = \n| map_image = \n| map_size = \n| map_caption = \n| title = First Minister\n| before_election = [[Nicola Sturgeon]]\n| before_party = Scottish National Party\n| after_election = \n| after_party = \n| opinion polling = Opinion Polling for the Next Scottish Parliament Election\n}}\n\nThe '''next Scottish Parliament election''' is scheduled to be held on 6 May 2021<ref name = \"dates act\">{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2016/13/enacted?view=plain |title=Scottish Elections (Dates) Act 2016 |work=legislation.gov.uk |publisher= |date= |accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref> under the [[Scotland Act 1998]], although this does not preclude the [[Scottish Parliament|Parliament]] being dissolved earlier. 129 [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|Members of the Scottish Parliament]] will be elected in the sixth [[election]] since the parliament was established in 1999.\n\n==Date==\nUnder the [[Scotland Act 1998]], an ordinary general election to the Scottish Parliament would normally have been held on the first Thursday in May four years after the [[2016 Scottish Parliament election|2016 election]], i.e. in May 2020.<ref name=\"ScotlandAct1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1998/46/section/2 |title=Scotland Act 1998 \u2013 Section 2 Ordinary General Elections |publisher=Office of Public Sector Information |accessdate=10 May 2016}}</ref> This would have clashed with the proposed date of a UK general election, although this became a moot point when a snap UK general election was held in [[2017 United Kingdom general election|June 2017]] (a further UK general election was held in [[2019 United Kingdom general election|December 2019]]).<ref name=\"clash\">{{cite web |url=http://news.scotland.gov.uk/News/Scottish-Elections-Dates-Bill-published-1f67.aspx |title=Scottish Elections (Dates) Bill published |publisher=Scottish Government |date=18 November 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604112556/http://news.scotland.gov.uk/News/Scottish-Elections-Dates-Bill-published-1f67.aspx |archive-date=4 June 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In November 2015, the Scottish Government published a Scottish Elections (Dates) Bill, which proposed to extend the term of the Parliament to five years.<ref name = \"clash\"/> That Bill was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 25 February 2016 and received Royal Assent on 30 March 2016, setting the new date for the election as 6 May 2021.<ref name = \"dates act\"/>\n\nThe date of the poll may be varied by up to one month either way by the [[British monarchy|monarch]], on the proposal of the [[Presiding Officer of the Scottish Parliament|Presiding Officer]].<ref name=\"ScotlandAct1\"/>\n\nIf Parliament itself resolves that it should be dissolved, with at least two-thirds of the [[Members of the Scottish Parliament|Members]] (i.e. 86 Members) voting in favour, the Presiding Officer proposes a date for an extraordinary general election and the Parliament is dissolved by the monarch by [[royal proclamation]].<ref name=\"ScotlandAct3\"/>\n\nIt does not necessarily require a two-thirds majority to precipitate an extraordinary general election, because under the Scotland Act Parliament is also dissolved if it fails to nominate one of its members to be [[First Minister of Scotland|First Minister]] within certain time limits, irrespective of whether at the beginning or in the middle of a parliamentary term.<ref name=\"ScotlandAct3\"/> Therefore, if the First Minister resigned, Parliament would then have 28 days to elect a successor (s46(2)b and s46(3)a). If no new First Minister was elected then the Presiding Officer would ask for Parliament to be dissolved under s3(1)a. This process could also be triggered if the First Minister lost a [[vote of confidence]] by a [[Majority|simple majority]] (i.e. more than 50%), as s/he must then resign (Scotland Act 1998 s45(2)). To date the Parliament has never held a confidence vote on a First Minister.\n\nNo extraordinary general elections have been held to date. Any extraordinary general elections would be in addition to ordinary general elections, unless held less than six months before the due date of an ordinary general election, in which case they supplant it.<ref name=\"ScotlandAct3\"/> However, this would not affect the year in which the subsequent ordinary general election will be held.<ref name=\"ScotlandAct3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1998/46/section/3 |title=Scotland Act 1998 \u2013 Section 3 Extraordinary General Elections |publisher=Office of Public Sector Information |accessdate=8 May 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Retiring MSPs==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | MSP\n! scope=\"col\" | Constituency/Region\n! scope=\"col\" | First elected\n! colspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Party\n! scope=\"col\" | Date announced\n|-\n| {{sortname|John|Finnie}}\n| [[Highlands and Islands (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Highlands and Islands]]\n| [[2011 Scottish Parliament election|2011]]\n| style=\"background:{{Scottish Green Party/meta/color}};\" |\n| [[Scottish Green Party|Green]]\n| {{dts|27 August 2019}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.holyrood.com/news/view,john-finnie-to-stand-down-at-2021-scottish-parliament-election_10724.htm |title=John Finnie to stand down at 2021 Scottish Parliament election |newspaper=Holyrood Magazine |first=Liam |last=Kirkaldy |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{sortname|Elaine|Smith|dab=Scottish politician}}\n| [[Central Scotland (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Central Scotland]]\n| [[1999 Scottish Parliament election|1999]]\n| style=\"background:{{Scottish Labour Party/meta/color}};\" |\n| [[Scottish Labour Party|Labour]]\n| {{dts|3 September 2019}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/cen